<TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=1 WIDTH="95%"><TR bgcolor="#D5E6E1"><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#000080" FACE="Verdana, Arial">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">grouchiegrumbles</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">okie, I am a 44 cleric, and just received my Celestial Healing capability.... so one of my guildies was harassing me with what if scenarios...  so I wanted to get some other peoples opinions on how they heal in the upper levels...<P>His scenario was, you are in a group, and your primary tank has 2k+ Hp's and is taking about 300 damage per second.... how are you going to heal him/her most effectively, and keep him/her alive.......<P>lets say the mob is unstunnable, and pretty durn magic resistant... just to put you into a defensive mood... but I wouldnt mind hearing offensive thoughts also....<P>I figured I might hit the tank with Celestial Healing(which from my computations is about 31 hp's per second), and follow it up with superior heals... my, thoughts were He/She wouldnt survive the 10 secs for complete heal... and, regardless one of us is most likely going down, either her/him from damage taken, or me from healing him and causing aggro...<P>but what would you all high levelers do in a case where your tank was getting the bejesus beat out of him/her...<P>thanks in advance for your thoughts...<P>  +Htoo Otoo -= Guild Wound Cleanser of the Furious Pantaloons -=- Sol Ro =-<P>PS - my real answer was "i would bend over and kiss the tanks arse goodbye, as I hit DA.. hehehehe"  but the test giver didnt take that answer to lightly.. hehehe</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Vladius</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Ok my primary tank only has 2k+ hps and is getting hit for 300 hp/sec. Do I:<P>A) /bye tank and run for the hills<BR>B) /bye tank, heal tank, /bye self<BR>C) /panic<BR>D) heal tank, /g EVAC!!!, cast divine aura when mob aggros on me, get left behind, /bye self<BR>E) heal tank, see how many dwarven ales I can slam before mob kills me</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Lhon</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">300hp per second is equivalent to 5 or 6 level 43 mobs pounding on a tank.  You can't keep up with that damage by yourself.  Either an enchanter gets them under control or the group evacs/dies.  The scenario is artificial.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Dikmer</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">/g You ARE the weakest link. Goodbye.<P>Cast DA, do the zoneline boogie.<P>Come back and res him when it's safe.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Kovina</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">With a tank of only 2k hit points (read under 3k), taking 300hp of damage a sec, there isn't anything you as a cleric can do. The only hope you have is that either there is another healer to assist (druid, shaman, cleric) and or another tank to share the damage. Both of those fall not upon you, but on other party members.<P>Gotta love these no win situations that people dream up. =)<P>Kovina Bloodfang<BR>54 Cleric</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Tommara</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I've actually been in situations almost as bad as that, fighting named Wyverns in Skyshrine.<P>The first time, I saw a level 53 warrior friend go down in seconds.  He wasn't in my group, but there was really nothing the cleric in the other group could do, especially being caught unawares of how hard this thing could hit.  The warrior crumpled like a paper doll.<P>Then the two tanks in my group took over, both rangers.  The warrior's quick death had scared us all.  I began chain casting Devine Light, and even that wasn't fast enough. It took the two rangers skillfully transferring aggro between them so I could have time to heal one, supplemented by a druid in my group who is a very good healer, and possibly with help from the other group's cleric as well.  Despite clarity and a necro pouring mana into me, I was OOM as the mob fell.<P>The second time we tried it went much better.  The warrior went in with Death Pact, Celestial Healing already cast before he engaged, and TWO clerics focussed on keeping him alive.  Hardly broke us out into a sweat that time.  <IMG SRC="http://eqcleric.gameglow.com/ubb/wink.gif"><P>So yeah, these situations can happen and Kovina is absolutely right.  It takes a group effort, and sometimes even help from another group.  Not only do the healers need to cooperate, but the tanks as well to buy the healers a little more time.<BR><P>------------------<BR>Tommara, Level 54 Vicar<BR>Tommar, Level 41 Ranger<BR>Povar</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Tommara</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">One correction - all the tanks in the above example probably had over 3500 HP, fully buffed.  <P>------------------<BR>Tommara, Level 54 Vicar<BR>Tommar, Level 41 Ranger<BR>Povar</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Nige Willowleaf</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">/agree that scenario is false and you all will die unless the enchanter gets it under control.<P>I have once in a while been lucky to get a CE on the right tank as the pull came in and then been able to use Remedy or Divine Light from then on. Well actually I pretty much do this all the time   <IMG SRC="http://eqcleric.gameglow.com/ubb/smile.gif"><P>I rarely use CH anymore unless I am in a very very tight mana situation and wish to be the utmost efficient. Also it is a preference of me and many of the  meleers I work with to be topped off before pulls come in.<P>I cast a remedy then follow with CE on my casters. I always use my fastest heal on a caster as the first heal.<P>I hate when I have to choose someone to die because I cannot cast fast enough to keep everyone alive, don't you? But then those rangers are used to it - LOL joking.<BR>------------------<BR><B><I>Nige Willowleaf</B></I><BR>60 Cleric <BR>Ayonae Ro Server<BR>Officer, Sphere of Transcendence<p>[This message has been edited by Nige Willowleaf (edited 04-04-2001).]</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Gniss Fleshmender</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Hmmm, 3k damage in 10 seconds, less than 3k hp... if it's just you and the warrior, let the warrior die and you run, you're WAY over your head. Retreat and res warrior.<P>Full group is a different story. You will either have a backup healer slinging spells with you, OR other tanks who can share the aggro, OR a wizard who will evac you, OR all three, multiple tanks, shammy/druid healer, druid/wizzy evac.<P><BR>In a controlled test setting, assuming several PLAYERS in an areana pounding on the warrior, as a test of your control over healing spells..... <BR>#1  Celestial healing is a 4 second cast, with one second recover. (recover may vary with computer system.) so figure 5 seconds without heals...1500 dmg...and then the first superior, another 4.5 seconds with 31hp regen at most in that time. that's about 9 seconds for 662 hp....warrior takes 2700 damage and is dead before the first SH lands.<BR>#2  Pure SH casting. Every 5 seconds warrior heals 600 hp and takes 1500 damage. net loss of 900 hp in that time. another 5 seconds, and if warrior has less than 2400 hp, (s)he is dead before second SH hits.<BR>#3  GH. 3.75 cast. 300 hp every 4 seconds in theory...warrior takes 1200 in that time. you'd get 2 heals if the warrior has over 2100 hp, then dead warrior.<P>In any case, the warrior will die. The BEST you can do is prolong his life by chaincasting GH. this has the potential of giving him another second or 2 of life, POSSIBLY allowing a second cleric time to CH him.<P>------------------<BR>The patchwork cleric<BR>Domus Divinae<BR>Prexus</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">grouchiegrumbles</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">okie, I understand the scenario was false, I just wanted to get an idea of how to go about TRYING to keep said tank alive...<P>I think getting a celestial Heal on the tank, either BEFORE or just as the MOB is being brought to the camp spot, would be an ideal situation.. and of course I realize that our situation would be better if we had other healers.. I just wanted to hear tactics people are using to heal in these cases...<P>also, if you have multiple mobs in this scenario wacking on your tank, you put ONE heal on that tank, and half those extra mobs are heading STRAIGHT for you, if not 99% of them...<P>Purpose of this scenario was to find out the tactics used in the high end game to keep tanks alive who are getting the serious beat down....  By all means, if you have other ideas / suggestions, I would love to hear them.... <P>I hope to learn, and also by others reading this, teach other clerics how to heal in the high end game....<P>thanks all for your replies, and please continue on!!!</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Rayne</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial"> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>Originally posted by grouchiegrumbles:<BR><B>okie, I understand the scenario was false, I just wanted to get an idea of how to go about TRYING to keep said tank alive...<P><SNIP><BR>Purpose of this scenario was to find out the tactics used in the high end game to keep tanks alive who are getting the serious beat down....  <SNIP><P>I hope to learn, and also by others reading this, teach other clerics how to heal in the high end game....<P>thanks all for your replies, and please continue on!!!</B><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>One reason people keep pointing this scenario out as very contrived is the numbers don't match up, particularly with respect to the high-end game.<P>300d/s is equivalent to a mob that at least double attacks for 300 a hit (or more).  That's definitely a high-end mob (read 60+).  Note: yes, there are some mobs that are not slowable, hit for 300 or more, and are not over 60 (eg. Kerdelb in Velketor's), but they are the exception.  Anyway, tanks fighting mobs like that are typically going to be buffed to 4k hps, maybe a lot more.  I know that between myself and the 60 Shaman we add about 1,800 hps to each tank.  So....<P>If possible I hit the tank with a Celestial Elixir before he engages and then go to Complete Heal if necessary.  Also, if the mob is really a bad ass then the tank should be using Evasive or Defensive.  If your tank can't do either, well, better kill the mob quick then because chaining CHeal is not going to happen long.<P>Rayne</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Kallain</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Two ways that your tanks are going to be taking this kind of damage. Overpull and uber mobs.<P>On an overpull, without an enchanter you will be dead. Divine Light and the unengaged mobs will make straight for you. DA, cancel it when the next heal is needed, repeat with DB if needed. If they aren't mezzed by this point then LOADING PLEASE WAIT...<P>On uber mobs the strategy seems to vary.<P>On Dain Frostreaver, each group gets a cleric. Tanks know that when they get agro, they disengage for CH. Im usually starting CH at about 60% in this situation. If the tank gets out, CH is already inbound and he is back in the fight fast. If he keeps the agro, CH wont get off in time and he will die. Tanks know this and learn to live with it. I always apologize for my miserable failure anyway. the tank can also sometimes get disengaged early. In this case, Cel Heal and back to the fight.<P>The guild I did Velkator with put 5 clerics and a bard in a group. Picked 3 main tanks and split 3 clerics to focus on the 1st main with the two remaining concentrating on the two backup tanks. CH was started as soon as the tank started taking damage. The raid was told that only these 3 tanks would be getting the cleric heals. Any other tank that got closest to Velk' would die. I think only three people died, one beeing the 1st cleric to CH the main tank.<P>Sometimes you mess up and people die, other times there is nothing you can do to keep them alive. If you mess up, always admit it. If you don't think there was anything you could do, tell them what you did, why you did it and let them know that in the same situation, you don't think there was anything you could do to improve on the outcome.<P>Sometime though, no explaination is necessary:<BR>You tell your party "CH a Selibite Juggernaut"<BR>You tell your party "Doh"<P>Kallain Ironsoul.<BR>Templar. Level 56, by the Grace of Brell.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Tommara</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">  <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>Originally posted by Kallain:<BR><B><BR>Sometime though, no explaination is necessary:<BR>You tell your party "CH a Selibite Juggernaut"<BR>You tell your party "Doh"<BR></B><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>Heh, I did that awhile back, but in Skyshrine.  Nobody died fortunately, but it sure woke them up.   <IMG SRC="http://eqcleric.gameglow.com/ubb/wink.gif"><P>------------------<BR>Tommara, Level 54 Vicar<BR>Tommar, Level 42 Ranger<BR>Povar<p>[This message has been edited by Tommara (edited 04-05-2001).]</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Thistleburr</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Greetings!<P>The numbers you give are from high end encounters. Your high end tanks will have other options available to them, such as the defensive discipline. If your defensive tank is still taking 300/sec (which would be a mob quadding 450) then you will have other clerics with you. At that point you define a tanking order and use Celestial Elixir and multiple Complete Heal casters.<P>------------------<BR><B>Thistleburr</B>, High Priestess of Bristlebane<BR><A HREF="http://www.the-elitists.com" TARGET=_blank><I>The Elitists</I></A>, Tribunal Server</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Aean</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">what if..... ok i'm not too familiar with the super high level monsters but lets use the example he gave. I'm asuming this is a controlled situation right. <P>Begin casting complete heal with a message that will tell the warrior at 5 seconds and 3 sesconds (5 just to prepare him) at 3 seconds he engages the mob which start givin him a pounding but you CH goes off and the mob goes straight for your throat. Now that he's gettin mad at you he'll stay off the warrior, would DA then work? if you cast it would the mob still stay attacking you or would he go for the warrior instead? if it stays on you couldn't you then cast DB and hope that in that amount of time the warrior could dish enough damage out that he'd kill the thing or agro the mob on himself so that when you got outa invul you could heal him up? just an idea, i dont' know if the da/db agro thing would work though but if it does maybe.... and if doesn't work would sitting down and medding while invul agro the mob onto you?</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Nige Willowleaf</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Thistleburr<P>I just wanna say....<P>I wanna be you when I grow up.<P>------------------<BR><B><I>Nige Wil